its a shitty map but also for some reason i dont really mind playing in it ill get to that later
its just too open and too big
u get faggots shooting at u from the other side of the map from nowhere while you dont have anybody on ur team anywhere near you
like its genuinely rare to see teammates on that map if ur not right at the spawn wave
ok maybe not but it feels like it
anyhow, despite being open its still full of bottlenecks you have to walk through to get to the middle or where anybody is
and anybody can just camp those bottlenecks from a million miles away because theres so little cover, so they do
it feels like you just have to get lucky to be able to walk around, i probably havent ever gotten more than care package on afghan ever in my life cause if you actually move around youre guaranteed to die to some retard from the other side of the map
i think all it comes down to is just who sees who first
because its so open and anybody can take pretty much any sightline, most fights are just you getting killed before even seeing the person who shot u, or even if you noticed them it being too late
sure the first shot advantage is a thing in any map, but in ones like afghan its different because youre simply not gonna be able to react to whos shooting
if its an overall smaller one like skidrow then even if you get shot first then you have a chance of reacting in time and winning still
but in afghan whoever is shooting you is probably going to be a speck on your screen and youll be dead before youre even able to notice them, all it comes down to is who notices the other one first, its like playing arma in cod

How do people like bowling? Enough to have dedicated bowling nights and whatnot? It's just slinging a ball across the floor. You play it for 15 minutes or so and get one strike, there you go, you've seen all bowling has to offer. It's not like it's particularly hard or exciting at all, you do it once and you've done it a million times. What's the appeal? Does it even have any? Or is just a time killer? Considering that nobody ever goes to do it by themselves, maybe it's just like a placeholder activity? When you wanna go out and do something people but have absolutely zero idea on what, you default to bowling.
But it's really dumb for that purpose as well, because there are a million things that sound more fun that bowling, there's no way that you can't think of one. Even just getting a few drinks and sitting down would be more enjoyable than bowling.
Although I guess that's basically kind of what bowling would be an accessory for, again, it still sounds incredibly lame. Literally anything else would be more enjoyable. Throw on a movie or something and watch that together, and there you go, way more fun of a background activity than bowling could be.
The only other reason for doing it could be the competitive factor, since I guess there is still somewhat of a skill ceiling to bowling, but, seriously, what kind of a friend group would have bowling as their hobby which they compete with each other in? People in their mid-fifties? I guess they'd like it, yeah, but I can't think of a reason that anybody normal would. And people who do it professionally, they likely just have mental illness.
I feel like it's one of the things that are definitely going to be lost in time. There probably won't be a single bowling alley around in the future. Do you see people deciding that they wanna hang out in a bowling alley, two or even a single generation ahead?

At least with golf, it's not the exact same thing every single time, you can have different angles and lengths to deal with which shake things up a little bit, there's some variety to it. And golf is still really shitty, so, it says a lot that it's better than bowling.
Really, all you do is throw a ball straight, and go "oooh" in your mind when it makes a few sticks tip over. And that's it. Over and over again. The "oooh" probably doesn't even happen after the fifth or so time you do it, and that's all bowling is.
I'll give it credit still, it could be okay for those 15 minutes that you play it and give you a bit of satisfaction from doing it well, but people genuinely have this as a "hobby" and get together in groups to have bowling nights and whatnot.
Just how do you think about all the things you could do with friends, and settle on bowling?
You swing a ball across the floor three times or something, and then sit down for another few minutes or so as you watch everybody else do the same thing, and then you get to do it again. Wow.
It's still shitty as a competition sport, because who gets excited about being the most competent at swinging a ball across the floor?
Bowling is so boring, that I think doing nothing and sitting around would be less boring. I can barely think of things that are more dull. Your brain should be incapable of being stimulated by bowling after passing the age of seven.
More power to people who do enjoy going bowling, but it's not like that's because bowling is actually any good of an activity, more so because it's just what they've gotten used to doing with their clique of fifty-year old drinking buddies, and they hang out in their designated bowling alley because it's simply what they do. It has to be a background activity.

Honestly, if you did actually enjoy bowling, then why would you go to a bowling alley for it? Think about it. If you have fun with bowling, then it's because you like slinging balls at things and feeling good about it, which I suppose could be an appeal to some. So, why wouldn't you just buy a bowling ball of your own, some things that you could hit with it, hell, alongside things that you can reuse you should also get a bunch of fruit or glass bottles, they'd explode once you hit them with the ball and all, that'd be cool and add a little bit of the flavor that bowling needs.
Anyway, yeah, just get some objects and go outside somewhere where nobody will bother you, and have your fun throwing the ball at them. Or, I guess you need a special surface that bowling alleys have for the ball to roll properly? Who cares? Just swing the thing towards at the stuff you want it to hit, have it fly through the air and hit them, wouldn't that actually be way more fun that having it roll down through the ground? Granted, I guess it would make you tired, but whatever, you're even getting some exercise then, works out.
You should be throwing the bowling ball through the air at stuff, not rolling it. That's always what I felt like doing when playing marbles as a kid. Imagine throwing a bowling ball full force and breaking a bunch of lined up shit with it. Infinitely more fun.
But, at the end of the day, maybe you should just go shooting instead. I'm pretty sure that whoever likes throwing heavy things at objects and seeing them break would enjoy a shooting range.
